[There are 2 lessons to be learnt from these ongoing reports from Manicaland: (1) When the farming community is unaware of the need to report suspect cases; this is characterised by them coming forward with reports when they see government activity; (2) the veterinary services are chasing after outbreaks, which is exhausting and not cost effective. It is economically and epidemiologically better to both maintain farmer awareness and to reinforce this by effective vaccination programmes ahead of the anthrax season, in this case at the end of the dry season. It is notably easier to get around on country roads during the dry season.

Maps of Zimbabwe can be seen at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/zimbabwe.pdf and http://healthmap.org/r/9R89. The location of Chipinge can be seen at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/ZI/00/Chipinge.html. Chipinge South is in Manicaland Province on the Mozambique border. - Mod.MHJ]
